A Russian named Igor Kolokov was arrested in Cairo on 29 January, 2003 and charged with assault on an Egyptian police officer who had attempted to arrest him for being drunk in public. Kolokov sells medical supplies throughout the Middle East and represents a company in Moscow called Medikat. A background check on Kolokov reveals that he was formerly an administrator at the Soviet institute Vector in Strizi, near Kirov in Russia. When he was arrested, Kolokov was carrying a card with a note on it reading [in Russian]: "Safrygin for H. Q., Peshawar."..
